"""
MKT Context Commentary — Genesis chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-genesis-1-3.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/genesis.json (v1 of ch1 already present; merge_comm skips it)

Key decisions in this range:
- ANE polemic orientation follows existing ch1:v1 context entry (Enuma Elish, Atra-hasis framing)
- Serpent treated as a created creature with ANE serpent-symbolism background; not identified as Satan
  (that is the NT retrospective reading, handled in mkt-christ layer)
- Garden-as-temple/sanctuary connection (Beale/Wenham) developed at v8, v15, v24
- Imago Dei as royal democratization (ANE kings as divine images → all humanity)
- Protoevangelium (v15) treated contextually; full Christological reading in mkt-christ
- Chiastic/poetic structures (v27) noted as literary form recognizable to ancient audience
- v1 already present — merge_comm will skip it safely
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

GENESIS_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": """<p>Genesis was composed in a world where Babylonian and Canaanite creation myths provided the dominant cosmological framework. The <em>Enuma Elish</em> (Babylonian creation epic, ca. 18th century BCE or earlier in oral form) portrays creation as emerging from conflict between Marduk and Tiamat (the chaos-water), with humans created from the blood of a slain god to serve the gods. The <em>Atra-hasis</em> similarly portrays humanity as created to do menial labor for gods. Genesis's polemic: creation comes not from divine conflict but from divine speech; creation is not chaotic violence but ordered goodness; humanity is not divine labor-fodder but the image-bearing vice-regent of YHWH. The literary parallels (waters, light, land, creatures, rest) show cultural contact; the theological inversions show deliberate counter-testimony.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>The primordial state described as <em>tohu wabohu</em> (formless and empty) and the deep (<em>tĕhôm</em>) carries resonance with Babylonian cosmogony. <em>Tĕhôm</em> is cognate with Babylonian <em>Tiāmat</em> (the salt-water chaos-dragon), though in Genesis it is not a divine opponent but simply the unformed deep awaiting order. The <em>Enuma Elish</em> begins: "When on high the heaven had not been named, firm ground below had not been called by name, naught but primordial Apsu, their begetter, and Mummu-Tiamat…" — a similar watery void. Genesis demythologizes: the deep is not a hostile divine power to be defeated, just the unformed substrate of creation. The <em>ruach</em> (Spirit/wind) of God hovering over the waters — the same word used for the divine wind driving back the sea at the Exodus (Exod 14:21) — signals the imminence of divine ordering.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>Divine speech as creative power was a concept known across the ancient world. The Egyptian <em>Memphite Theology</em> (the Shabaka Stone, ca. 700 BCE, preserving older tradition) describes Ptah creating "everything and all the divine order" through the word (<em>hw</em>) conceived in his heart and articulated by his tongue. In Mesopotamian theology, the spoken command of a great deity had creative power (<em>Enuma Elish</em> depicts Marduk demonstrating divine authority by commanding a constellation to disappear and reappear). In Genesis, the creative word is even more absolute: no battle, no prior material, just divine command and instantaneous result. The brevity — "God said. And there was" — is itself a literary expression of effortless sovereignty.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>The evaluative refrain "God saw that it was good" (<em>wayyar ʾĕlōhîm kî-ṭôḇ</em>) runs six times in chapter 1 and is elevated to "very good" (<em>ṭôḇ mĕʾōḏ</em>) at the conclusion. This stands in sharp contrast to creation myths where creation is morally ambiguous (the <em>Enuma Elish</em> never evaluates creation as good; Babylon was created from the torn corpse of Tiamat). Genesis's insistence on goodness is a theological declaration: the material world is not contaminated, evil by nature, or the battleground of warring powers. The separation (<em>yabdel</em>) of light from darkness is an act of sovereign ordering — the same word used for Israel's separation from the nations (Lev 20:24) and the priest's separation of holy from common.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>In the ancient Near East, the act of naming was an act of sovereignty and definition — to name something was to establish its nature and assert authority over it. Pharaoh renamed conquered peoples; Mesopotamian kings named newly-built cities after themselves to assert permanent ownership. When God names the Day (<em>yôm</em>) and Night (<em>lāylāh</em>), he establishes his lordship over time itself. The evening-to-morning sequence ("there was evening, and there was morning") reflects the ancient calendar beginning at sunset — the Israelite liturgical calendar, the Jewish Sabbath, and the rabbinic day all run from evening to evening, a pattern embedded in creation's own structure.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>The <em>rāqîaʿ</em> (expanse/firmament, v6) reflects the ANE cosmological model of the sky as a solid beaten-out dome — the root <em>rāqaʿ</em> means "to hammer out" (like metal-working; cf. Isa 42:5; Job 37:18: "Can you beat out the skies with him, hard as a cast metal mirror?"). In the Babylonian cosmology of the <em>Enuma Elish</em>, Marduk splits Tiamat's body in half, raising one half as the sky to hold back the upper waters. Genesis uses the same cosmological model — a domed sky separating upper and lower waters — while entirely eliminating the mythological violence. The waters above the <em>rāqîaʿ</em> are the source of rain (Job 38:22-33; Ps 148:4).</p>""",
    "7": """<p>The second creation day's completion is confirmed by the standard separation formula but notably lacks the "it was good" evaluation — the only day without it (ancient commentators including the rabbis of <em>Bereshit Rabbah</em> noticed this absence and debated its significance). One strand of interpretation: the work of the second day was incomplete — the separation of waters above and below was begun, but only completed on day 3 when the lower waters were gathered and dry land appeared. The "it was good" then applies twice on day 3 (vv10, 12), compensating for the absent second-day evaluation. This architectural pattern of the creation week was a feature of later Jewish liturgical interpretation of the text.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>The naming of the expanse "Sky" (<em>šāmayim</em>) completes the second day's work. In ANE cosmology, <em>šāmayim</em> (dual form: "the two heavens"?) encompassed both the visible sky and the divine realm above it. The Babylonian cosmological map shows three heavens above the earth, each inhabited by different categories of divine being. Israel's use of <em>šāmayim</em> for both the visible sky and the divine dwelling ("the heaven of heavens cannot contain you," 1 Kgs 8:27) preserves this vertical-register cosmology while refusing to populate the heavens with warring deities.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>The gathering of the waters and the appearance of dry land carries a polemic edge against the Canaanite storm-god cycle. In the <em>Ugaritic Baal Cycle</em> (ca. 13th–12th century BCE), Baal's primary adversary is Yam (Prince Sea/River) — the sea is a divine opponent that must be defeated for land and order to be established. In Genesis, the sea (<em>yām</em>) is merely gathered by divine command; it presents no resistance. The sea that Canaanite religion worshiped as a deity is here simply a place where YHWH tells the water to go. The later Exodus narrative (YHWH separating the Red Sea and then commanding it to return) deliberately echoes this creation sovereignty over the waters.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>The naming of the dry ground "Land" (<em>ʾereṣ</em>) and the gathered waters "Seas" (<em>yammîm</em>) continues the sovereignty-through-naming pattern. For Israel, <em>ʾereṣ</em> carried the specific resonance of the promised land — the land given by YHWH was not simply territory but a share in YHWH's own created domain. The theological connection between creation's "land" and the covenant's "land" (used 1,500 times in the OT) was available to any Israelite reader of Genesis: the land promised to Abraham was first spoken into existence by YHWH in Genesis 1.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>The phrase "according to their kinds" (<em>lĕmînô</em>, leminehu) appears 10 times in Genesis 1–2, framing creation as ordered and reproducible — each kind reliably producing its own kind. In the ancient world, the stability of plant and animal kinds was experienced as a given of existence (unlike our modern awareness of evolutionary change); Genesis grounds this experienced stability in divine creative order. The creation of vegetation on day 3, before the sun appears on day 4, is a structural inversion of agricultural expectation: in the narrative logic, the pattern is theological (land + vegetation belong together on day 3; luminaries + creatures on days 4–5) rather than an attempt at scientific chronology.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>The land "producing" vegetation (the land as creative agent, prompted by God's command) reflects the ancient understanding of the earth as a participant in creation, not merely passive matter. Israel's agricultural experience — planting seeds, waiting for rain, tending crops — involved a partnership with a responsive earth. The covenantal framing of land-productivity in Deuteronomy (the land yields its produce when Israel obeys; the land withholds when Israel rebels, Deut 11:13-17; 28:1-5,15-18) builds on this creation-pattern: the land is a responsive participant in the covenant between YHWH and his people.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>The third day's evening-morning closure contains two "it was good" evaluations (vv10, 12) — one for the gathering of seas and appearance of land, one for vegetation — compensating for the absent evaluation on day 2. This doubled affirmation on day 3 creates a symmetrical pattern with day 6 (also two acts: land creatures and humanity), which also contains two evaluations — though in day 6's case the second becomes "very good." The architectural balance of the six-day structure was an important feature of the text for ancient readers who understood literary symmetry as a mark of compositional intention.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>The luminaries are created to serve as "signs for sacred times (<em>mô ʿădîm</em>), and for days and years." <em>Mô ʿădîm</em> is the precise word used for Israel's appointed festivals in Leviticus 23 ("These are the <em>mô ʿădîm</em> of YHWH which you shall proclaim as holy convocations"). The sun and moon are therefore given a liturgical function from creation: they mark the rhythm of Israel's worship calendar. Passover is at the full moon in Nisan; Sukkot is at the full moon in Tishri; the new moon (<em>roʾsh ḥōdesh</em>) was itself a regular festival. Israel's entire sacred calendar was built into the luminaries at creation.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>The functional role of the luminaries — "to give light on the earth" — establishes their instrumental purpose before their physical identity is described. This narrative ordering (function before form) reflects the logic of Genesis 1's cosmological presentation: what matters about the luminaries is not their intrinsic nature but their role within the created order YHWH has established. In contrast to the Babylonian <em>Enuma Elish</em>, which opens with the naming of the great lights as divine beings (<em>Anshar, Kishar, Anu</em>), Genesis treats the lights as tools created for a function, not as personalities with intrinsic divine dignity.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>The deliberate refusal to name the sun and moon — calling them only "the greater light" (<em>hammāʾôr haggāḏôl</em>) and "the lesser light" (<em>hammāʾôr haqqāṭōn</em>) — is the most pointed anti-mythological moment in chapter 1. The normal Hebrew words for sun (<em>šemeš</em>) and moon (<em>yārēaḥ</em>) are also the names of Canaanite solar and lunar deities (Shamash/Shemesh was worshiped throughout the Levant; Yarih/Yareach was the moon god of Ugarit). Genesis avoids these names entirely, using circumlocutions instead. The three-word dismissal of the stars — "he also made the stars" (<em>wĕʾēt hakkôḵāḇîm</em>) — reduces the objects of intense Babylonian astrological veneration to a subordinate clause in the creation narrative.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>The luminaries are "set" (<em>wayyittēn</em>, placed/appointed) in the expanse by God — the same verb used for setting officials in positions of authority. In Egyptian theology, the sun-god Re traveled across the sky in his solar boat, actively governing the cosmos; in Babylonian theology, Shamash was the judge of heaven who actively directed human affairs. In Genesis, the luminaries occupy the expanse like appointed functionaries: their position and purpose are given to them by the Creator, not self-generated. The theological implication: the cosmos runs not by autonomous divine forces but by appointed agents under the one sovereign Creator.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>The governance of "day and night" and the separation of "light from darkness" by the luminaries (v18) creates a structural echo of day 1 (v4-5), where God himself performed the same separation. The luminaries are God's deputies for an ongoing function that God established directly on day 1. This pattern of divine action → delegated continuation is the creation-template for how YHWH relates to human institutions: he establishes order directly, then delegates its maintenance to appropriate agents (kings, priests, families). The luminaries' faithful daily governance of day/night was YHWH's visible testimony of his covenant faithfulness (Jer 31:35-36).</p>""",
    "19": """<p>The fourth day's closure marks the midpoint of the creation week. Days 1–3 establish the realms (light/dark, sky/water, land/sea + vegetation); days 4–6 fill those realms (luminaries, sea/air creatures, land creatures + humanity). This "framework interpretation" of the creation week — where the two triads correspond structurally — was recognized by Aqaba, Augustine, and modern scholars (Meredith Kline, Henri Blocher). Whether or not one reads the days as chronological, the literary architecture of the creation week communicates total, ordered completion in a way immediately legible to an audience trained in the sevenfold completeness of Israel's liturgical calendar.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>The waters and air are commanded to "teem" (<em>šāraṣ</em>) and "fly above the earth across the expanse." The word <em>šāraṣ</em> is used for swarming creatures in general — it appears in the plagues of Egypt (Exod 7:28; 8:3 — frogs swarming from the Nile) and in Levitical purity laws (Lev 11:10-12, swarming creatures in the water). The creation of sea and air creatures on day 5 precedes land creatures (day 6) in a progression from the most remote (oceanic) to the nearest (land, where humans live). The narrative pace quickens as creation approaches its apex.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>The great sea creatures (<em>tannînîm</em>, v21) were the specific opponents of YHWH in Canaanite and Israelite cosmic-combat poetry. Ugaritic texts describe Lotan (<em>ltn</em>, cognate with Hebrew <em>liwyātān</em>) as "the fleeing serpent, the twisting serpent, the mighty one with seven heads" — defeated by Baal. Isaiah 27:1 and Psalm 74:13-14 use this cosmic-combat imagery for YHWH's victory over Leviathan/Tannin. Genesis 1:21 is a deliberate counter-statement: the creatures that other peoples' myths elevated to divine opponents YHWH simply "created" (<em>wayyiḇrāʾ</em>, the same verb as Gen 1:1) as part of the fifth day's work. They are not adversaries; they are creatures. The demythologizing is complete in a single word: <em>bārāʾ</em>.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>The first divine blessing (<em>wayĕḇāreḵ</em>) in the Bible is given to sea creatures and birds: "Be fruitful and increase in number and fill the water in the seas, and let the birds increase on the earth." Blessing in the OT is generative power — the divine enabling of life and reproduction. The same blessing will be given to humanity in v28 and to Abraham in 12:2. The fact that non-human creatures receive the blessing first establishes that God's generative care for creation is broader than his care for humanity, encompassing the entire biosphere. The fruitfulness mandate for creatures is never revoked — even after the Flood, YHWH reiterates it (9:1, 7).</p>""",
    "23": """<p>Day five's completion formula ("there was evening, and there was morning — the fifth day") marks the only point in the creation week where naming (<em>qāraʾ</em>) does not occur: God names the realms (days 1–3) but not the creatures. The naming of creatures will be delegated to Adam (2:19-20). This distinction between what God names directly and what he delegates to humanity is the first hint of the image-bearing mandate: humanity will extend God's creative-organizing work through the exercise of language and naming.</p>""",
    "24": """<p>The creation of land animals on day 6 uses the same "after their kinds" language as the vegetation (vv11-12) and sea creatures (vv21), establishing the ordered diversity of the entire biotic creation. Three categories of land animals are distinguished: <em>ḇĕhēmāh</em> (livestock/domestic animals), <em>remeś</em> (creatures that move along the ground/small animals), and <em>ḥayyat-hāʾāreṣ</em> (wild animals/beasts of the field). This tripartite classification reflects practical Israelite categories rather than modern taxonomy: animals are classified by their relationship to human habitation and use.</p>""",
    "25": """<p>The fifth and sixth "it was good" evaluations of land animals precede the creation of humanity, establishing that the material creation in its non-human form is fully affirmed before the human appears. This ordering resists any reading that elevates humanity at the expense of the rest of creation: YHWH's approval of creation is not contingent on the presence of humanity. The created order has value in itself, not merely instrumental value as background for the human story. This theological point was important for Israel's understanding of the Sabbath (when human productive work ceased, creation continued to be good).</p>""",
    "26": """<p>The <em>imago Dei</em> ("Let us make mankind in our image, in our likeness") carries specific ANE political valence. In Mesopotamia and Egypt, the king was routinely described as the "image" (<em>ṣalmum</em> in Akkadian, <em>tzalmu</em> in Hebrew) of the deity — the deity's physical representative on earth. Pharaoh was the image of Amun-Re; Assyrian kings set up their "images" (<em>ṣalamī</em>) in conquered territories as tokens of their sovereign presence. Genesis 1:26 applies this royal-image designation to all humanity without restriction of gender, ethnicity, or social rank — every human being is the royal image-bearer and vice-regent of YHWH. This was a radical democratization in an ancient world where royal-divine status was the exclusive privilege of monarchs.</p>""",
    "27": """<p>The chiastic structure of v27 — "God created mankind in his own image, / in the image of God he created them; / male and female he created them" — is the most carefully balanced poetry in Genesis 1. The chiasm (A-B-A' / B-A structure) was a recognizable literary form in the ancient world; its presence marks this verse as the literary apex of the creation narrative. "Male and female he created them": both genders fully and equally bear the divine image — a significant statement in ancient Near Eastern context, where women's social and religious status was substantially lower than men's. Neither gender is derivative; both share fully in the royal-priestly image-bearing vocation.</p>""",
    "28": """<p>The dominion mandate uses explicitly royal-administrative language: "fill the earth and subdue it (<em>kiḇšûhā</em>); rule (<em>rĕḏû</em>) over the fish… birds… and every living creature." <em>Kāḇaš</em> can mean to subdue/trample underfoot (it is used for military subjugation, Num 32:22,29; 2 Sam 8:11) and <em>rādāh</em> means to rule/have dominion over (the same word for Solomon's administrative rule in 1 Kgs 5:4). This is not exploitation language but viceregal language: humanity is appointed as YHWH's royal administrator of the creation, accountable to the sovereign who delegated the mandate. The king of Israel was meant to exercise this dominion-pattern as an image of the divine king; the failure of Israel's kings to do so rightly is the OT's central political tragedy.</p>""",
    "29": """<p>The original diet granted to humanity is explicitly vegetarian: "every seed-bearing plant… every tree that has fruit with seed in it" — all vegetation, but no animal life. This is corroborated by v30, where animals are similarly given only green plants. The absence of authorized killing in the original creation order is significant: no sacrifice, no hunting, no slaughter. The permission to eat meat is granted only after the Flood (9:3: "Everything that lives and moves about will be food for you"). Later prophetic visions of eschatological restoration include the return of non-violent relationships between predators and prey (Isa 11:6-7; 65:25), suggesting the original vegetarian creation is also the eschatological telos.</p>""",
    "30": """<p>The extension of the food-grant to "all the beasts of the earth and all the birds in the sky and all the creatures that move along the ground" emphasizes that YHWH's provision is for all living things, not only for humanity. The phrase "everything that has the breath of life in it" (<em>nišmat-ḥayyîm</em>) is the same phrase used for human life in 2:7 — a deliberate verbal connection placing humans and animals under the same life-sustaining provision of the Creator. Psalm 104, the creation Psalm that parallels Genesis 1 most closely, develops this theme at length: YHWH gives food to young lions (v21), provides for the great sea creatures (v26), and opens his hand to satisfy the desire of every living creature (v28).</p>""",
    "31": """<p>The final evaluation "very good" (<em>ṭôḇ mĕʾōḏ</em>) — with the intensifier <em>mĕʾōḏ</em> (very/greatly) — marks the completion of the entire creation as a unified whole. The move from six "good" evaluations to one "very good" is a narrative crescendo: what was individually good in each part is "very good" in its totality. The rabbis debated what the "very good" added (Bereshit Rabbah 9:5: "Rabbi Meir said: it refers to death — very good means death is very good, for without death humans would not strive or achieve"). The evaluative conclusion stands as Genesis's declaration against any cosmological dualism: the material world in its entirety, including its diversity and complexity, is the product of deliberate good work.</p>"""
  },
  "2": {
    "1": """<p>The completion formula "Thus the heavens and the earth were completed in all their vast array" (<em>ṣĕḇāʾām</em>) uses the word for "host" or "army" — the same word for the heavenly armies (<em>ṣĕḇāʾôt</em>, "YHWH of Armies/Hosts"). The creation in its completed form is a marshaled, organized whole — creation as the divine army deployed in its appointed stations. The title "YHWH of Hosts" (<em>YHWH ṣĕḇāʾôt</em>), used over 280 times in the prophets, draws on this creation-completion image: the God who organized all creation is the God who commands the heavenly armies in defense of his covenant people.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>The divine "rest" (<em>wayyišḇōt</em>, from <em>šāḇat</em>) on the seventh day is the creation-basis for the Israelite Sabbath (Exod 20:11: "For in six days the LORD made the heavens and the earth… and rested on the seventh day"). John Walton and others have argued that day 7 in ANE cosmological contexts often represents a deity "taking up residence" in a newly built temple after its completion — the cosmic temple inauguration ending in the divine rest. The Babylonian <em>Enuma Elish</em> ends with the dedication of Esagila (Marduk's temple in Babylon) and a divine feast/rest. If Genesis 1 is a cosmic-temple inauguration text, the Sabbath rest is YHWH taking up residence in the cosmos as in his sanctuary.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>God "blessed" the seventh day (<em>wayĕḇāreḵ</em>) and "made it holy" (<em>wayĕqaddēš</em>) — the only entities explicitly blessed and sanctified in the creation account are the creatures (v22), humanity (v28), and the seventh day (2:3). The holiness of time precedes the holiness of space (the tabernacle, the temple) in Genesis's narrative sequence. The institution of Sabbath rest is the first act of consecration in the Bible — before any altar, any sacrifice, any sanctuary, the seventh day is set apart as sacred. Sabbath observance in Israel was therefore participation in the primordial rhythm of creation itself.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>The formula "This is the account of" (<em>ʾēlleh tôlĕḏôt</em>) appears ten times in Genesis (2:4; 5:1; 6:9; 10:1; 11:10; 11:27; 25:12; 25:19; 36:1; 37:2) and serves as the book's structural organizing device — each <em>tôlĕḏôt</em> introduces a new narrative section. At 2:4, this formula introduces the second creation account, and with it the first appearance of the divine personal name YHWH (the covenant name revealed to Moses in Exod 3:14-15, but known from patriarchal times). The shift from <em>ʾĕlōhîm</em> alone (ch1) to <em>YHWH ʾĕlōhîm</em> (ch2-3) marks the beginning of the personal covenant narrative: the transcendent Creator of ch1 is the same as the personal, present YHWH who walks in the garden.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>The pre-agricultural conditions of v5 — "no shrub of the field… no plant of the field had yet sprung up, for YHWH God had not sent rain on the earth and there was no one to work the ground" — establish two preconditions for cultivated plant life: rain from above and human cultivation from below. The phrase "no one to work the ground" frames humanity's creation in agricultural terms from the outset. This reflects the subsistence agricultural context of ancient Israel, where the land's fertility depended on both divine provision (rain) and human labor (plowing, sowing, tending). The absence of both in the pre-human creation world signals that human presence is creation's missing element.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>The mysterious <em>ʾēḏ</em> (usually translated "mist" or "streams") that watered the whole surface of the ground in the pre-rain world has no other biblical occurrence and may derive from the Akkadian <em>edû</em> (subterranean flood-water, the cosmic underground sweet-water ocean called <em>apsu</em> in Sumerian/Babylonian cosmology). The <em>apsu</em> was understood in Mesopotamia as the underground fresh-water reservoir that fed springs, wells, and rivers from below. If this is the referent, Genesis 2:6 describes the pre-rain world as watered entirely from below — a subterranean water system — which changes at or after the Flood (when rain begins as the primary water source). This would be consistent with the later description of the flood as the opening of both "the windows of heaven" and "the springs of the great deep" (7:11).</p>""",
    "7": """<p>The formation of humanity from "dust of the ground" (<em>ʿāpār min-hāʾăḏāmāh</em>) echoes ANE creation-from-earth imagery while inverting its valuations. The Babylonian <em>Atra-hasis</em> describes Enki and the birth-goddess forming humans from clay mixed with the blood and flesh of a slain god (<em>We-ilu</em>) — humanity's essence is partly divine but also partly dead and divine. The Sumerian story of Enki forming humans from clay to do the work of the lesser gods is structurally similar. Genesis: no divine blood, no slain deity, just earth and the directly applied divine breath (<em>nišmat ḥayyîm</em>). The <em>ʾādām/ʾăḏāmāh</em> (human/humus) wordplay grounds human identity in the earth they are to tend — not in divine violence or servile function but in creative relationship with the created order.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>The Garden of Eden as a sacred space has significant parallels to the ANE concept of a divine garden. Mesopotamian texts describe paradise gardens associated with the gods (the garden of the sun-god Shamash in the Gilgamesh epic; the sacred grove of Anu). The Sumerian paradise <em>Dilmun</em> — described in the Enki and Ninsun myth as a pure, clean, bright place where no sickness existed — has conceptual resonance with Eden. The structural parallels between the garden and Israel's tabernacle/temple are significant: both face east (Ezek 43:1-4; 44:1), both contain precious metals and stones (2:11-12; Exod 25-28), both feature cherubim guardians (3:24; Exod 25:18-22), and both are described as the place of divine presence. The garden is creation's original sanctuary, and the sanctuary is creation's garden restored.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>The two special trees — the tree of life (<em>ʿēṣ haḥayyîm</em>) and the tree of the knowledge of good and evil (<em>ʿēṣ haḏaʿat ṭôḇ wārāʿ</em>) — stand "in the middle of the garden," the axis of the sacred space. The tree of life has Mesopotamian parallels: Gilgamesh seeks the "plant of life" (<em>šammu ša balāṭi</em>) at the bottom of the cosmic ocean; Assyrian palace reliefs depict the sacred tree (<em>kiskanu</em>) at the center of the divine garden. The tree of the knowledge of good and evil is unique to Genesis. "Knowledge of good and evil" likely carries the sense of comprehensive experiential wisdom — the full range of human experience — which properly belongs to divine maturity rather than to creatures at the beginning of their existence under divine tutelage.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>The river that flowed from Eden and separated into four headwaters (v10-14) places the garden at the source of the ancient world's known river systems. The cosmic river in ANE thought often originated in the divine realm and flowed outward to water the inhabited world. In the Babylonian world map (<em>mappa mundi</em>), Babylon stood at the center of the earth surrounded by water — a cosmological centrality that Genesis transfers to Eden. The river from Eden becoming the four great rivers of the known world suggests Eden as the cosmic center — the omphalos — from which life flows outward.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>The Pishon, winding through the land of Havilah "where there is gold," is unidentified with certainty; proposals include the Indus, a river in Arabia, or the Wadi Bisha in Saudi Arabia. Havilah as a gold-rich land appears also in Gen 10:7,29 (associated with descendants of both Ham and Shem), suggesting Arabia or East Africa. The interest in gold, <em>bĕḏōlaḥ</em> (aromatic resin/bdellium), and onyx (<em>šōham</em>) — the specific precious materials named in vv11-12 — connects Eden directly to the tabernacle: bdellium appears in the description of manna (Num 11:7), and onyx stones appear in the high priest's ephod (Exod 28:9). Eden's precious materials foreshadow the materials of Israel's sanctuary.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>The <em>šōham</em> (onyx) stone mentioned in v12 is one of the twelve gemstones on the high priest's breastplate (Exod 28:9,20) and one of the adornments of the "guardian cherub" in Ezekiel 28:13 — a passage that conflates the Eden narrative with a "prince of Tyre" oracle, explicitly referencing Eden's precious stones as the original divine adornment. The gold of Eden is "good" (<em>ṭôḇ</em>), using the same evaluative term as the creation week, establishing continuity between the creation's "very good" and the material excellence of paradise. Israel's sanctuary was built from the finest materials precisely because it was meant to be a microcosm of Eden restored.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>The Gihon is identified as winding through "the entire land of Cush" — in OT usage Cush typically refers to sub-Saharan Africa (Ethiopia/Sudan), but it can also designate areas in Mesopotamia (cf. Gen 10:8, where Nimrod son of Cush is associated with Mesopotamian cities). If Cush here means a Mesopotamian region, the four rivers could all be Near Eastern. If it refers to Africa, the river system is of legendary/cosmic scale. The association of the Gihon with Cush/Africa gives Eden a geographic scope that encompasses the ancient world from Arabia to Ethiopia to Mesopotamia — Eden is not a local paradise but the source of the whole world's water.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>The Tigris (<em>ḥiddeqel</em>) and Euphrates (<em>pĕrāt</em>) are the two great Mesopotamian rivers and the waterways along which the major ANE civilizations of Babylon, Assyria, and Sumer developed. Their presence in the Eden river-system grounds the paradise narrative in recognizable Mesopotamian geography. For an Israelite audience familiar with Mesopotamia as the origin-land of both the patriarchs (Ur of the Chaldeans, Gen 11:31) and the exile (Babylon), the connection of Eden to Mesopotamian rivers gave the paradise narrative a historically-grounded geography. The Euphrates in particular was the boundary of the promised land at its greatest extent (Gen 15:18; 1 Kgs 4:21).</p>""",
    "15": """<p>The verbs for Adam's work in the garden — "to work it" (<em>lĕʿāḇdāh</em>) and "to take care of it" (<em>lĕšomrāh</em>) — are linguistically identical to the verbs used for the Levitical priests' work at the tabernacle (Num 3:7-8: "They are to perform duties for him and the whole community at the tent of meeting by doing the work [<em>ʾāḇad</em>] of the tabernacle. They are to take care of all the furnishings of the tent of meeting, fulfilling the obligations of the Israelites by doing the work [<em>šāmar</em>] of the tabernacle"). Adam in the garden is therefore, from the beginning, a priest in the cosmic sanctuary, called to priestly service in the divine dwelling-place. The later institution of the Levitical priesthood is a restoration of the original human vocation.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>The covenant-command structure of vv16-17 mirrors the suzerain-vassal treaty form known from Hittite treaties (14th–13th century BCE): (1) the great king's identity, (2) his historical gifts to the vassal (here: the provision of every tree for food, v16), (3) a specific stipulation (the one prohibition, v17a), (4) a curse for violation (the death-consequence, v17b). The covenant with Adam in the garden is the first covenant in biblical history — structurally analogous to the later Sinaitic covenant but simpler: one gift, one law, one consequence. The gift precedes the prohibition: the freedom and generosity of the command ("from any tree you may freely eat") frames the single restriction in the context of abundance.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>The consequence stated for eating from the tree of the knowledge of good and evil — "you will certainly die" (<em>môt tāmût</em>, emphatic infinitive absolute + imperfect) — is the death-warning that structures the entire subsequent narrative of Genesis. The emphatic double-verb construction "dying you will die" (literally) marks this as a solemn, authoritative declaration. Adam and Eve do not die immediately on the day of eating; instead they enter the process of dying (physical mortality, spiritual separation from YHWH's life-giving presence). Theological debate about "the day" of death runs from Philo through the Church Fathers to the Reformation: the most consistent reading takes "day" as the period within which the process begins rather than an immediate physical death on the calendar day.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>The first negative divine assessment in the entire creation narrative — "it is not good (<em>lōʾ-ṭôḇ</em>) for the man to be alone" — creates a structural counterpoint to the seven "good" evaluations of chapter 1. Creation is incomplete, and the incompleteness is relational: the human creature requires another of comparable nature for his full functioning. The word <em>ʿēzer</em> (helper) is applied to YHWH himself as Israel's helper in numerous psalms (Ps 121:2; 124:8; 146:5) and never implies inferiority — a helper is one who supplies what is lacking in the one helped. The phrase <em>kĕnegdô</em> (corresponding to him / suitable for him) emphasizes complementary equivalence rather than subordination.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>The naming of the animals (vv19-20) is both a cognitive exercise and a royal-administrative act. In the ANE, the ability to name — to define the essential nature of things and establish one's authority over them — was a marker of wisdom and sovereignty. Egyptian pharaohs named conquered peoples and territories; divine figures in Mesopotamian myths named the natural phenomena they governed. Adam's naming of the animals demonstrates his exercise of the image-bearing mandate (1:26-28) in concrete form: he is the divine image-bearer who exercises dominion through the faculty of language. The narrative also functions to establish the dramatic need: no <em>ʿēzer kĕnegdô</em> was found among the animals, heightening the solution when it comes.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>The summary of Adam's naming ("the man gave names to all the livestock, the birds in the sky and all the wild animals") without finding a suitable helper creates one of the narrative's most elegant structural silences. The entire catalogue of creation — animals both domestic and wild, birds, all the inhabited earth — cannot provide what the single human needs. This is not a commentary on the inadequacy of the rest of creation but a demonstration that the human creature is of a different category — one that requires a relational counterpart of the same kind. The second creation account's entire dramatic movement leads to v23: the first human words, celebrating the first human meeting of equals.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>The "deep sleep" (<em>tardēmāh</em>) that YHWH causes to fall on the man is the same word used for the trance-sleep that falls on Abram in the covenant ceremony of Genesis 15:12 — where YHWH alone passes between the divided covenant animals while Abram is unconscious. Both instances involve a divine creative act that the human does not witness and cannot control: the deep sleep signals that what is about to happen is entirely God's work, not the man's. The rib (<em>ṣēlāʿ</em>) is also translated "side" — it is used for the "side" of the tabernacle planks (Exod 26:20), of the ark (Exod 25:12), and of the temple (1 Kgs 6:5,8) — suggesting that the word carries connotations of structural completeness rather than merely a single bone.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>YHWH "built" (<em>wayyiḇen</em>) the woman from the man's rib/side — the verb is the standard word for constructing a building (house, city, wall), and it is the same word used for building the tabernacle and temple. The woman is architecturally constructed, not merely formed from earth as the man was. YHWH then "brought her to the man" — a narrative echo of the marriage ceremony where the father "gives" the bride to the groom (Exod 22:17; Judg 15:2). YHWH acts as the father of both parties, and the first marriage in human history is performed by the divine Father. This framing gave ancient Israelite marriage ceremonies their theological weight: a human marriage recapitulates the first marriage that YHWH himself performed.</p>""",
    "23": """<p>The man's exclamation "bone of my bones and flesh of my flesh" (<em>ʿeṣem mēʿăṣāmay ûḇāśār mibĕśārî</em>) is the covenant-recognition formula used throughout the OT for affirming kinship and tribal solidarity. When all the tribes of Israel came to David and said "We are your bone and flesh" (2 Sam 5:1), when David's messengers addressed the elders of Judah with "You are my brothers, my bone and flesh" (2 Sam 19:12), they were using this same formula to acknowledge covenant kinship. Adam's recognition of the woman is therefore a formal covenant-recognition speech — the first covenant bond in human history, expressed in the ANE language of mutual recognition and commitment. It is also the first human poetry in the Bible: creation's apex is celebrated in verse.</p>""",
    "24": """<p>The editorial comment "Therefore a man shall leave (<em>yāʿăzōḇ</em>) his father and mother and hold fast (<em>wĕḏāḇaq</em>) to his wife and they shall become one flesh" uses covenant-fidelity vocabulary. <em>ʿĀzaḇ</em> (leave/forsake) is the word for abandoning covenant loyalties (Judg 2:12: Israel "forsook" YHWH; Jer 1:16: they "forsook" YHWH). <em>Dāḇaq</em> (hold fast/cleave) is the characteristic word for covenant loyalty: Israel was commanded to "hold fast" to YHWH (Deut 10:20; Josh 22:5; 23:8). The marriage institution is thus described in the vocabulary of covenant loyalty — marriage is not merely social or biological but covenantal. In an ANE context where patrilineal clan identity was supreme, the instruction that a man prioritize his wife over his parents was a significant social claim.</p>""",
    "25": """<p>The nakedness-without-shame state of v25 is the inverse of the shame and clothing that follow the Fall in 3:7,21. In the ANE honor-shame culture, nakedness was profoundly shameful — it was the condition of slaves, prisoners of war (2 Sam 10:4-5), and the humiliated (Isa 47:3; Lam 1:8). The primal state of unselfconscious nakedness before each other and before YHWH indicates complete relational transparency — no self-protection, no fear of exploitation, no competitive striving for advantage. This is the state that the entire biblical narrative moves to restore: the New Jerusalem's inhabitants no longer need clothing as protection against shame because the Fall's relational distortions are finally undone (Rev 3:18 still addresses nakedness; Rev 21:1-4 moves beyond it).</p>"""
  },
  "3": {
    "1": """<p>The serpent in the ancient Near East was a complex religious symbol. In Egypt, the <em>uraeus</em> (cobra) was the royal divine emblem worn on the pharaoh's crown, representing the protective power of the goddess Wadjet; serpents were associated with the wisdom of the god Thoth. In Mesopotamia, serpents were associated with the healing-god Ningishzida and with immortality (the Gilgamesh epic's plant of immortality is stolen by a serpent). In Canaanite religion, serpents were fertility symbols associated with Baal and Asherah. Genesis describes the serpent as "more crafty (<em>ʿārûm</em>) than any of the wild animals YHWH God had made" — crafty/shrewd rather than evil by nature; it is a created creature. The later NT identification of the serpent with Satan (Rev 12:9; 20:2) is a theological retrospective that Genesis does not supply explicitly; the narrative presents a created creature that speaks deceptive counsel.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>The woman's response to the serpent accurately restates the permission ("we may eat fruit from the trees in the garden") but has already begun to be shaped by the serpent's framing — his question deliberately overstated the restriction ("must not eat from any tree?") to make the prohibition seem absolute. The woman corrects this, but the conversation itself is already a concession: she is engaging the serpent's framing rather than simply dismissing the distorted premise. In ANE thought, engaging with a divine-status figure (whether god or semi-divine creature) carried implicit risk — one was entering their rhetorical domain. The woman is in the serpent's conversational space from v2 onward.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>The woman adds to God's command "and you must not touch it" — a phrase absent from God's original prohibition in 2:17. Whether this is her own precautionary addition (a "fence around the Torah" in rabbinic terminology — adding an extra restriction to protect against violating the core prohibition), a tradition developed in the community of two, or simply a paraphrase, it slightly distorts the original prohibition. The rabbinic tradition <em>syag laTorah</em> ("a fence for the Torah") was recognized even in this verse as a protective instinct; but in this context the slight exaggeration of the restriction may make it easier for the serpent to chip away at its credibility.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>The serpent's counter-assertion "You will not certainly die" (<em>lōʾ môt tĕmûtûn</em>) directly contradicts the divine death-warning of 2:17 (<em>môt tāmût</em>). Both use the emphatic infinitive-absolute construction — the serpent matches the emphatic force of the divine command with an emphatic denial. In ANE divine-court discourse, one divine figure countering another's decree was not unprecedented (in the Atrahasis flood narrative, Enki countermands Enlil's flood-decree to protect Utnapishtim). The serpent is positioning himself as an alternative divine authority, suggesting that God's death-warning is not final or accurate — the first recorded theological dispute in human history.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>The serpent's explanation — "God knows that when you eat from it your eyes will be opened, and you will be like God (<em>kēʾlōhîm</em>), knowing good and evil" — appeals to the desire for divine-status wisdom. In the ANE, wisdom (<em>ḥokmāh</em>) was the prized attribute of gods and kings; Mesopotamian wisdom literature (the <em>Counsels of Wisdom</em>, the <em>Instructions of Shuruppak</em>) reflects the human quest for the kind of comprehensive, reliable knowledge that only divine beings fully possess. The serpent frames the prohibition as divine self-protection — God is keeping something good from humanity — rather than as divine care for humanity's development. This inversion of YHWH's character (generous provider → jealous withholder) is the serpent's primary deception.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>The triple evaluation of the fruit — good for food (<em>ṭôḇ... lĕmaʾăkāl</em>), pleasing to the eye (<em>taʾăwāh... lĕʿênāyim</em>), desirable for gaining wisdom (<em>neḥmāḏ... lĕhaśkîl</em>) — mirrors the language of v9 where the trees are described as "pleasing to the eye and good for food." The serpent's reframing has shifted the woman's perception of the tree from YHWH's evaluation (forbidden because of its nature) to a consumer's evaluation (desirable for its benefits). The triad — bodily desire, visual beauty, intellectual ambition — has been read since the Church Fathers as a taxonomy of temptation (1 John 2:16 uses similar triadic language: "the lust of the flesh, and the lust of the eyes, and the pride of life"). "She gave some to her husband, who was with her" — Adam's passive presence and eating without resistance is noted without comment by the narrator.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>The opening of the eyes and recognition of nakedness was what the serpent promised ("your eyes will be opened," v5), but the result is the opposite of the wisdom-through-transcendence the serpent implied. They gained experiential knowledge of vulnerability, shame, and broken relationship — the "good and evil" of fallen existence rather than divine wisdom. Fig leaves (<em>tĕʾēnîm</em>) were the specific material chosen; figs were associated with fertility and prosperity in the ancient Near East (Deut 8:8; 1 Kgs 4:25; Mic 4:4 — "each person under their own fig tree" = the good life). The choice of fig leaves for clothing is ironic: fertility-associated leaves as the covering for shame. The self-manufactured covering will prove inadequate (v21: YHWH replaces it).</p>""",
    "8": """<p>The image of YHWH "walking in the garden in the cool of the day" (<em>mithallēk baggān lĕrûaḥ hayyôm</em>) is anthropomorphic and intimate — the Creator on an evening stroll through his garden-sanctuary. <em>Lĕrûaḥ hayyôm</em> (literally "in the wind/breath of the day") may indicate the early afternoon breeze that cooled the Levantine day — a specific, realistic time-detail. The Hithpael form <em>mithallēk</em> (regular/habitual walking about) suggests this was YHWH's customary garden presence — not an unusual visit but the normal divine-human communion that the garden represented. Hiding "among the trees" (<em>bĕtôk ʿēṣ haggān</em>) is the exact inverse of the garden's purpose: the trees that provided nourishment and beauty now provide cover against the divine presence.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>YHWH's question "Where are you?" (<em>ʾayyekkāh</em>) is the first divine question addressed to a human in Scripture — God has spoken commands (1:28; 2:16-17) but not yet asked a question. Rhetorical questions addressed by omniscient YHWH to humans recur throughout Genesis: "Where is your brother Abel?" (4:9), "Where have you come from? Where are you going?" (16:8), "Is anything too hard for YHWH?" (18:14). These questions are not requests for information but invitations to accountability and self-disclosure. The question "Where are you?" calls the hiding human out of concealment into the presence of the one he cannot ultimately escape (Ps 139:7-12).</p>""",
    "10": """<p>Adam's answer reveals the psychological impact of the Fall: "I heard you in the garden, and I was afraid because I was naked; so I hid." Fear (<em>yārēʾ</em>) appears here for the first time in Scripture as a human experience — and it is fear of YHWH, not of an external threat. The innocent nakedness of 2:25 (no shame) has become fearful nakedness (v10). The consciousness of the body as exposed and vulnerable is a product of the broken relationship with the Creator. In ANE thought, to stand before a great king or deity required careful preparation and covering; improper appearance before the divine throne was dangerous. The Fall has made the ordinary condition of embodied human existence feel like unauthorized approach to the divine presence.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>YHWH's counter-question — "Who told you that you were naked? Have you eaten from the tree I commanded you not to eat from?" — is a prosecutorial interrogation that establishes the chain of causation: naked awareness derives from the prohibited eating. In the ANE legal context, guilt was established through confession and witness; YHWH's questioning of Adam, then Eve, then the serpent follows the standard ancient Near Eastern judicial procedure of examining each party in the order of their involvement. The divine court convened in the garden to adjudicate the first legal case in human history, with YHWH as both accuser and judge.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>Adam's response — "The woman you put here with me — she gave me some fruit from the tree, and I ate it" — is the first instance of blame-shifting in human history, and it implicates God himself ("the woman you put here with me"). The structure of the sentence places the woman first and the man's own action ("I ate") last and in the passive position — linguistically minimizing his own agency. In ANE legal contexts, shifting responsibility to another party was a recognized defensive strategy. The man's failure to fulfill the <em>šāmar</em> (guarding/keeping) function of his priestly vocation (2:15) is implicitly condemned in his response: rather than defending the woman from the serpent's deception, he acquiesced and now blames her.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>The woman's response to YHWH's question — "The serpent deceived me, and I ate" — is more accurate than Adam's in that the serpent's deception is documented in the narrative. The word "deceived" (<em>hišîʾanî</em>) is significant: Paul uses the cognate Greek verb (<em>ēpatēsen</em>) in 2 Cor 11:3 and 1 Tim 2:14 to describe Eve as "thoroughly deceived" — genuine deception, not mere rationalization. The narrative presents Eve as deceived and Adam as knowingly disobeying (1 Tim 2:14 explicitly distinguishes: "Adam was not the one deceived; it was the woman who was deceived"). Notwithstanding the deception, the responsibility is not absolved: YHWH does not ask the serpent "why did you do this?" with the same interrogative-invitation he gave Adam and Eve; the serpent receives only pronouncement of judgment.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>The serpent's curse — "cursed are you above all livestock and all wild animals; you will crawl on your belly and eat dust all the days of your life" — uses "eating dust" as the image of the lowest possible existence. In Mesopotamian underworld mythology, the dead "eat clay and dust, drink muddied water" (Ishtar's Descent to the Underworld); dust-eating was the condition of the dishonored dead. The permanent crawling posture becomes the emblem of the adversary's ultimate destiny — prostration and defeat. The curse on the serpent is the only divine speech in vv14-19 not addressed as "you" to a human being; the serpent is addressed without the interrogative process, confirming its different moral status.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>The promise of enmity between the serpent's seed and the woman's seed — "he will crush your head, and you will strike his heel" — is the <em>prōtoevangelion</em> (first gospel), the foundational promise that structures the entire OT narrative of conflict between two lines. In ANE context, the image of a head-crushing victory over a serpent-enemy appears in combat imagery: Egyptian pharaoh-as-warrior crushing the snake-enemy, Babylonian Marduk crushing Tiamat. The seed of the woman is described as winning the decisive victory (head-crushing) at the cost of a non-fatal wound (heel-strike). The tension of the promise — victory through vulnerability — establishes the pattern of how YHWH's redemption will unfold throughout Scripture.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>The consequences pronounced for the woman address two spheres of her life: motherhood and marriage. "Pain in childbearing" — the word <em>ʿiṣṣāḇôn</em> (pain/toil) is the same word used for the man's toil in v17, emphasizing that the consequences are structurally parallel, not disproportionate. Maternal mortality in the ancient world was significant (Jacob's wife Rachel dies in childbirth, 35:16-19; the narrative names it without euphemism). "Your desire will be for your husband and he will rule over you" — the word <em>tĕšûqāh</em> (desire) appears only three times in the OT (here; Gen 4:7 for sin's desire for Cain; Song 7:10 for the Beloved's desire). The original equal partnership of the garden (2:18-24) is now marked by distortion — whether the desire is longing that leads to domination or a competitive drive, it represents the disruption of the original complementary union.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>The ground (<em>ʾăḏāmāh</em>) is cursed "because of" (<em>baʿăḇûrĕḵā</em>) the man — not as punishment of the earth itself but because of the human's role as its steward. The ecological consequences of human rebellion are a theme the prophets develop extensively: the land mourns when Israel sins (Hos 4:3; Jer 12:4; Amos 8:8), the ground vomits out its inhabitants when they defile it with idolatry and injustice (Lev 18:25,28). The man who was appointed to tend and keep the garden-sanctuary (2:15) has, through his rebellion, cursed the very ground he was meant to cultivate. The anguish of agricultural toil — fighting thorns and thistles, laboring for an often-meager harvest — was the daily experience of the ancient Israelite farmer, now given its theological origin.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>Thorns (<em>qôṣ</em>) and thistles (<em>dardār</em>) are the emblems of cursed, unworked land throughout the OT prophetic literature: Isaiah uses them as images of divine judgment on the vineyard (Isa 5:6), on the land of Edom (Isa 34:13), and on neglected fields (Isa 7:23-25). Hosea declares the altar of Israel will be thorns and thistles (Hos 10:8). The thorns-and-thistles curse links the ecological disorder of the fallen creation directly to the human rebellion, connecting every farmer's battle with weeds to the primordial moment of disobedience. The crown of thorns at the crucifixion (Matt 27:29; John 19:2) carries this creation-curse symbolism: Christ bearing on his head the sign of the cursed creation.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>The mortality sentence — "dust you are and to dust you will return" — grounds human death in the creation-from-dust narrative of 2:7. Death is not a divine design feature but a consequence of the broken covenant: the life that was sustained by relationship with YHWH is now draining away. The Mesopotamian tavern-keeper Siduri in the Gilgamesh epic offers essentially the same mortality prognosis as divinely ordained from creation: "When the gods created humankind, they allotted death for humankind, but life they retained in their own keeping." Genesis makes the same observation but with a crucially different etiology: death entered through a specific transgression, not through original divine design. The death-entry-through-sin framework is the basis for Paul's argument in Romans 5:12: "sin entered the world through one man, and death through sin."</p>""",
    "20": """<p>Adam's naming of the woman "Eve" (<em>ḥawwāh</em>) — derived from <em>ḥāyāh</em> (to live) or <em>ḥāwāh</em> (to breathe/live) — after the curse-pronouncements is a signal of faith within judgment. To name her "mother of all the living" (<em>ʾēm kol-ḥāy</em>) after receiving the death-sentence is to assert the continuation of the life-mandate. The naming also recalls Adam's first naming of the animals (2:19-20) and his covenant-recognition speech (2:23) — the marital covenant is reasserted through naming even in the shadow of mortality. Later Jewish tradition connected the name Eve to the divine promise of the serpent-crushing seed: she is the mother of "all the living," including the one who will undo death.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>YHWH's provision of "garments of skin" (<em>kātnôt ʿôr</em>) to replace the inadequate fig-leaf aprons is the first provision in Scripture that requires the death of an animal. The narrative does not describe the killing, but the garments presuppose it — skin implies a slaughtered animal. The same word <em>kuttōnet</em> (garment/tunic) is used for the high priest's distinctive garment (Exod 28:4; 39:27; Lev 8:7) and for Joseph's coat of many colors/long sleeves (37:3) — both priestly and covenant-significant garments. The pattern: human self-coverage is inadequate; divine provision of adequate coverage requires a substitutionary death. This is the creation-basis for the entire sacrificial system in which a dying animal provides the covering that sinful humanity requires.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>The divine deliberation — "The man has now become like one of us (<em>kĕʾaḥaḏ mimmennû</em>), knowing good and evil" — echoes the divine plural of 1:26 ("let us make") and the serpent's promise of 3:5 ("you will be like God"). The partial fulfillment of the serpent's promise is acknowledged: the experiential knowledge of good and evil has been attained, but through transgression rather than divine gift. The closing of access to the tree of life is therefore an act of mercy within judgment: immortality in a state of sin-death would be permanent condemnation rather than everlasting life. YHWH prevents the permanent entrenchment of fallen humanity in an immortality that would make redemption impossible.</p>""",
    "23": """<p>The expulsion from Eden parallels the expulsion patterns of the ancient Near East's most severe punishments: to be driven from the divine presence was the ultimate curse. Akkadian texts describe the withdrawal of the personal protective deities (<em>šedu</em> and <em>lamassu</em>) from a sinner as the precondition of all other misfortune. Psalm 51:11 reflects this terror: "Do not cast me from your presence or take your Holy Spirit from me." The garden as sanctuary and Adam as priest: the expulsion is not merely geographic but cultic — the priest-king of Eden is removed from the cosmic sanctuary he was appointed to tend. From this point in Genesis forward, the narrative follows the trajectory toward the restoration of access to the divine presence — tabernacle, temple, and finally the eschatological city where "the dwelling of God is with man" (Rev 21:3).</p>""",
    "24": """<p>The cherubim (<em>kĕrûḇîm</em>) stationed at the east of the garden to guard the way to the tree of life are divine throne-attendants and sanctuary guardians throughout the OT. In the tabernacle, golden cherubim flanked the mercy seat of the Ark of the Covenant, their wings overshadowing the place of divine presence (Exod 25:18-22). In Solomon's temple, enormous carved cherubim dominated the Holy of Holies (1 Kgs 6:23-28). Ezekiel's chariot-throne vision features living cherubim as the divine chariot (Ezek 1; 10). The cherubim at Eden guard the way back to the tree of life — access to the divine presence is now barred, and the entire sacrificial system of Israel is the divinely-instituted way of approaching (but not yet fully entering) that presence. The east-facing expulsion from the garden and the east-facing entrance to the tabernacle/temple together suggest the sanctuary is the partial restoration of what the garden was: a place of YHWH's accessible presence, requiring proper mediation.</p>"""
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'genesis')
    before_count = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    merge_comm(existing, GENESIS_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'genesis', existing)

    result = load_comm('mkt-context', 'genesis')
    after_count = sum(len(v) for v in result.values())
    print(f'  Verses added: {after_count - before_count}')
    for ch in [1, 2, 3]:
        ck = str(ch)
        n = len(result.get(ck, {}))
        print(f'  Ch {ch}: {n} verses present')
    total_chs = len(result)
    total_vv = sum(len(v) for v in result.values())
    print(f'  Genesis context total: {total_chs} chapters, {total_vv} verses')
    print('Genesis 1–3 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
